<h2 p align="center">III</h2>
<h2 p align="center">Worry</h2>
<h3 p align="center">Worry</h2>
<h4 p align="center">(Worry)</p>
<h2 p align="center">---</p>
The words bleed into the reader eagerly. What the words lack in hands, they steal. What's more, the reader provides more in writing, to the more in reading, and so on in this way.
What is God? A Truth? A celestial? A Law? A Knowing? All of these things? Useless navel-gazing? It is certainly one thing at its core: An idea. Information. Conceived of thought. Words with teeth. A predilection so stubborn when gotten hold of, that you could never do away with it. A dreadful curse. A life is framed around the idea or in spite of it. Or the thought is sealed with black drapes.
I could feel myself being born the first time a thinking thing died, or looked into a night sky. Of course people have always managed that trouble well enough, one might reason it's a natural part of life! But what is well enough alone? Progress is a drug. Forward motion is its own reward. Every solution is packaged with a thrilling new echelon of problems. Every patched hole gets you two new leaks. A stitch in time makes nine. Every scientist conceives a new idiot.
We’ll never know what the world used to be, or what God was, because that was an old worry, and the people that resolved it continue to pick at the idea like an almost-healed scab. They’ll suffer lack of context into eternity. They have killed the mundane now and forever, but will continue in their hopeless search for magic.
I can tell you before the Initiative started, these words weren’t possible, their lives didn’t make sense, and that world wasn’t something we could process today. But I know. The Book remembers. And people can sense it. A week ago a local aesthete flung itself off a bridge, and the poor thing died thinking it was crazy. But life goes on all the same, even if the fundamentals have been changed, even if now we have to deal with things like philosophers or kings.
What was the precise moment that it happened? How did it happen? The answer to both of these questions is yes. It happened in the snow with arcane tools, it was an exquisite dish, it happened in some sort of general, metaphysical way, in which there was much consternation. Every crux will be its own answer.
But this doesn't answer the question? How was God killed? Which is the wrong question. A God cannot be killed, or figured. It cannot be fathomed at all. It cannot be changed. It cannot be created, or destroyed, and the efforts of the Initiative were always a useless, narcissistic diversion. Its extensions Law, and Truth, likewise, permanent and unchangeable. So here we are. Or there we were. Things weren't always this way, but one cannot describe a nothing, and once, people never conceived of things like God or milkmen.
Before the Initiative asked their questions, and ripped this world kicking and screaming out of the hole, there was something called a bahmalow. If I had to make it understandable to a human being, it's like the feeling you get when you've been holding it in for a while, but all across your body. This is the last stage of its life cycle. It is a relatively common meteorological phenomenon.
In the last world there was something called a Worry-Worry. I guess it could be indirectly described as a lump of skin and arms in the shape of a ball. You see it and your ears are ringing sharply. It appears around corners, or accidentally in crowds. Sometime a bit far away down the street. You remember seeing it and suddenly you're aware that you've been motionless for minutes. You lick your lips. A nosebleed trickles into your mouth. You swallow the blood. The air is overwhelmed with the perfume of ozone and copper. Static needles dance on your skin. And you can't pull your eyes away.
Before the Initiative conceived of a God at all, or forgot that they had already killed it, they thought up something called an Idea. This however, I can't find a parallel to. You didn't ask and you couldn't know.
